	(450,1,'2013-06-20 15:20:35','2013-06-20 19:20:35','<h1><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">[icon name=\"icon-bolt\"]Educational Games</span></h1>\r\nYoung learners today are being consumed by the convergence of technology with education. Educational games and technology are part of their world more then ever. As technology becomes more accessible through phones, mobile consoles, gaming devices, laptops and tablets, there is a massive potential to give your student the upper hand advantage in comparison to other students. Give them the right tools and they will flourish.\r\n\r\nA recent report on <strong>educational games</strong>was produced in March of 2013. This report was funded by the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and carried out by SRI International. The research examined 77 studies that were conducted and focused on learning outcomes. The results of their finding were remarkable:\r\n<blockquote>When digital games were compared to other instruction conditions without digital games there was a moderate to strong effect in favor of digital games in terms of broad cognitive competencies (g+ = 0.32, 95% CI [.19, .44]). This is equivalent to a 62% success rate in the digital game groups relative to a 50% success rate in the other instruction conditions (defining success as the median of the other instruction control conditions). This means that the students at the median in the control group (no game) could have been raised 12% in cognitive learning outcomes if they had received the digital game.</blockquote>\r\nYour students are in the most competitive time in history. The world has become flat. Content is produced all over the world and available instantly to anyone. Students have access to more information than when you grew up and also have more pressure to compete in this global environment. How do you give your student a better chance? Do you know how they compare against the rest of the world? Do you even know how they compare against kids in th